\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The Chinese Remainder Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this section, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring with identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 be ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
relatively prime 
\series default
or 
\series bold
comaximal 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $I+J=R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In other words, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in J$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y=1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=a\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J=b\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a,b)=1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then their product is 
\begin_inset Formula $IJ=\{x_{1}y_{1}+\cdots+x_{k}y_{k}\mid x_{i}\in I,\,y_{i}\in J,\,k\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, if 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{n}$
\end_inset

 are ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then their product is 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{n}=\{x_{11}x_{12}\cdots x_{1n}+\cdots+x_{k1}x_{k2}\cdots x_{kn}\mid x_{ij}\in I_{j},\,k\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $IJ\subseteq I\cap J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap J\subseteq IJ$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap J=IJ$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots,I_{k}$
\end_inset

 are pairwise relatively prime (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{i}+I_{j}=R$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{k}=I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We have 
\begin_inset Formula $I\cap J=(I\cap J)(I+J)\subseteq IJ$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We prove by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is 
\begin_inset Formula $(1)$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose the statement is true for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots I_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\in I_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}\in I_{k}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}+y_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i<k$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $1=(x_{1}+y_{1})\cdots(x_{k-1}+y_{k-1})\in I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1}+I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k}=(I_{1}\cdots I_{k-1})\cap I_{k}=I_{1}\cdots I_{k}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (The Chinese Remainder Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1},\dots I_{k}$
\end_inset

 be pairwise relatively prime ideals in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R/I_{1}\cdots I_{k}\cong R/I_{1}\times\cdots\times R/I_{k}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:R\to R/I_{1}\times\cdots\times R/I_{k}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(r)=(r+I_{1},\dots,r+I_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Check that this is a ring homomorphism with kernel being 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\cap\cdots\cap I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
